Menoeceus the son of Creon was said to have sacrificed him· self when Thebes was besieged by the seven chiefs. Teiresias the seer prophesied that if he did so the Thebans would gain the

victory (EuripideS, Phoenissae, v. 913). J ux enal likes a stroke at Greek history (see x.174); he therefore goes out of his way, and having spoken of Thebes he adds the legend of Cadmus sowing the dragon' s teeth from which the Thebans sprung, and says the soldiers whom this sowing pro- duced fell to fighting straightway as if a trumpeter had been born with them. From the earliest times to the present the trumpet in some shape has been used for battle signals, in all nations civilized and uncivilized. Ruperti thinks these verses are “parum opportuni,” and betray too much engerness on the poet’s part to ex- hibit his art and learning. Such learning certainly must have astonished all Rome.
